05586nam a22012495i 9780691231242DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20211997nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806912312427 a10.1515/97806912312422doi  a(DE-B1597)581235  a(OCoLC)1257323750  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 7aLIT0041302bisacsh04a873.011 aComparetti, Domenico, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aVergil in the Middle Ages /cDomenico Comparetti. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2021] 4cÂ©1997  a1 online resource (392 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tTABLE OF CONTENTS -- tIntroduction -- tAuthor's Preface to the First Edition -- tPART I. THE VERGIL OF LITERARY TRADITION -- tPART II. THE VERGIL OF POPULAR LEGEND0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFrom its first complete Italian printing in 1872 up to the present day, Domenico Comparetti's Vergil in the Middle Ages has been acknowledged as a masterpiece, regarded by some critics as "a true and proper history of European consciousness from antiquity to Dante." Treating Vergil's poetry as a foundation of Latin European identity, Comparetti seeks to give a complete history of the medieval conception of the preeminent poet. Scholars of the time had transformed Vergil into a sage and a seer, a type of universal philosopher--even a Christian poet and a guide of a Christian poet. In the mid-twelfth century, there surfaced legends that converted Vergil into a magician, endowing him with supernatural powers. Comparetti explores the ongoing interest in Vergil's poetry as it appeared in popular folklore and legends as well as in medieval classical scholarship. This great synthesizing work, which has been unavailable for over twenty years, is now back in print, based on E.F.M. Benecke's 1895 translation of the Italian second edition. Comparetti begins with the period in which Vergil lived and goes on to evaluate how the later images, particularly the legends, of Vergil coincide with the more scholarly accounts of his life. The result is a grand sweep of literary history from the first century B.C.E. through the end of the Middle Ages, with implications for the nineteenth century and the rise of Italian nationalism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / General.2bisacsh  aAeneid.  aArs Notoria.  aBe Continentia.  aCaesar.  aChristianity.  aCronica di Partenope.  aDe Viris Illustrious.  aDiable boiteux.  aDivina Commedia.  aDolopathos.  aEuropean literature.  aGesta Bomanorum.  aGleomades.  aGolden Legend.  aHoly Scriptures.  aMirabilia.  aMons Virginum.  aMutatorium Caesaris.  aMythologicon.  aNodes Atticae.  aNovellino.  aOtia Imperialia.  aParzival.  aPolycraticus.  aQuaestiones Naturales.  aRenart contrefait.  aSalvatio Bomae.  aSette Savi.  aSpeculum historale.  aVergilian poems.  aWunderkind.  aa propos.  acantores francigenarum.  aecclesiastical.  aenthusiasm.  agrammatical works.  ahabundantia.  aimaginem.  aintellectual productivity.  alofty speculations.  amovements.  aoccidentation.  apar excellence.  ascholasticism.  aspontaneous expansion.  asufficiently.  atrue knowledge.  avere glisceus.  avice versa.  avolgare illustre.1 aBenecke, E. F.M.1 aZiolkowski, Jan M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Archive 1927-1999z978311044249640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691231242zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691231242423Coveruhttps://www